  <section class="faq">
    <div class="container">
      <h2 class="section-title">Frequently asked questions</h2>
      <div class="faq-list">
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>What is TDEE?</h3>
          <p>
            Total Daily Energy Expenditure estimates the total calories you burn in a full day combining your basal metabolic rate with the energy cost of movement, exercise, work, and daily activity. In practice it is calculated as BMR multiplied by an activity factor from sedentary to very active. TDEE is your maintenance intake band when averaged over time—eating near TDEE helps stabilize weight while allowing normal life rhythms. Treat this calculator’s TDEE as an estimate; adjust using your measured weight trend over several weeks.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>What is BMR here?</h3>
          <p>
            Basal Metabolic Rate is the calorie burn your body needs at complete rest to sustain breathing, circulation, organ function, and basic repair. This page estimates BMR with the Mifflin–St Jeor equation using sex, age, height, and weight before any activity multiplier is applied. BMR usually makes up a large fraction of total daily expenditure for sedentary people and remains the anchor when you change activity settings. It is still not a lab measurement—clinical indirect calorimetry can differ from equation predictions.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>Why doesn't my scale weight move exactly with the target?</h3>
          <p>
            Day-to-day scale changes reflect water retention, sodium shifts, stress hormones, digestive contents, and menstrual cycle phases—not just fat mass. A steady deficit does not plot as a straight line on the bathroom scale because glycogen and fluids fluctuate faster than adipose tissue changes. We recommend comparing weekly averages and multi-week slopes instead of single readings after high-salt meals or intense workouts. Sleep and stress also influence perceived stalls even when fat loss continues slowly.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>Is aggressive weight loss safe?</h3>
          <p>
            Very large deficits can raise fatigue, strength loss, micronutrient gaps, and medical risks—especially alongside chronic illness, pregnancy, adolescence, or eating-disorder history. Aggressive settings may be inappropriate for people on medications that affect appetite, glucose, or electrolytes. Always prefer medically supervised plans if you have cardiac, renal, or endocrine conditions and you want fast loss. If a goal feels unsustainable, slow the pace and reassess with a clinician or registered dietitian.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>Are the macro grams prescriptive?</h3>
          <p>
            The protein, carbohydrate, and fat grams shown here come from splitting your calorie target using a fixed 30/40/30 template and standard energy densities (4/4/9 kcal per gram). That split is a teaching example—not a personalized meal plan for athletes, diabetes, renal diets, or therapeutic ketogenic protocols. People who strength train often keep calories similar but raise protein; endurance athletes may tilt carbohydrate higher. Ask a dietitian when clinical nuance matters.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>Are my stats uploaded?</h3>
          <p>
            No—this tool runs entirely in your browser and does not send your age, body size, or outputs to our servers. There is no account storage, cloud sync, or third-party analytics tied to your inputs for this calculation pathway. Clearing the page or closing the tab discards locally shown numbers. Review your browser privacy settings if you share devices with others.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>How many calories should I eat per day to lose weight?</h3>
          <p>
            Subtract 500-750 calories from your TDEE (maintenance calories) for a safe weight loss rate of 0.5-0.75 kg (1-1.5 lbs) per week. For example, if your TDEE is 2,200 kcal, target 1,450-1,700 kcal/day. Never go below 1,200 kcal (women) or 1,500 kcal (men) without medical supervision. Use the calculator above to find your exact target — select "Lose weight — moderate" as your goal.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>What is the difference between BMR and TDEE?</h3>
          <p>
            BMR (Basal Metabolic Rate) is the calories your body burns at complete rest — just to stay alive. TDEE (Total Daily Energy Expenditure) is BMR multiplied by your activity level — it's the total calories you burn in a day including exercise and daily movement. TDEE is always higher than BMR. You should eat based on TDEE (not BMR) to determine your weight loss or gain target.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>Is the Mifflin-St Jeor formula accurate?</h3>
          <p>
            The Mifflin-St Jeor equation is considered the most accurate BMR predictor for most healthy adults, as endorsed by the Academy of Nutrition and Dietetics. It's more accurate than the older Harris-Benedict formula by approximately 5%. However, it's still an estimate — actual BMR can vary by ±10% due to genetics, thyroid function, body composition, and metabolic adaptation. Use the result as a starting point and adjust based on real-world weight changes over 2-4 weeks.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>How do I count calories effectively?</h3>
          <p>
            Start by calculating your daily target using this calculator. Then track food intake using a food diary, kitchen scale (most accurate), or a calorie tracking app. Focus on tracking consistently rather than perfectly — even approximate tracking builds awareness of portion sizes and calorie-dense foods. Common high-calorie culprits: cooking oil (120 kcal per tablespoon), nuts (160+ kcal per handful), sugary drinks (150-300 kcal per glass), and restaurant meals (often 50-100% more calories than home-cooked equivalents).
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

